  <brief_title>Pulse Pressure Variation Measured During Valsalva Maneuver to Predict Fluid Responsiveness Under Open-chest Condition</brief_title>
  <official_title>Pulse Pressure Variation Measured During Valsalva Maneuver to Predict Fluid Responsiveness Under Open-chest Condition in the Patients Undergoing Off-pump Coronary Arterial Bypass Grafting</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Samsung Medical Center</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Samsung Medical Center</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Pulse pressure variation (PPV) is a well-known dynamic preload indicator to predict fluid
      responsiveness. However, its usefulness in open-chest conditions has been equivocal. The
      investigators evaluated whether PPV measured during Valsalva maneuver can predict fluid
      responsiveness after sternotomy.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
